Data Exploration on Ford GoBike Trips¶

by Dane Lovell Gonzales¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset contains information about individual rides made in Ford GoBike bike-sharing system in February 2019, covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 16 columns and 183412 records. Some data quality issues need to be addressed, such as missing data and incorrect data types.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest will be the trip's duration and start time.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features containing user information / membership will be explored. These are the user type, gender, birth year, and whether the trip was taken under the "Bike Share for All" program.

Cleaning the Data¶

In [9]:
# create a copy of the dataframe to be used for cleaning
bike = df.copy()

Deal with missing data¶

It is not possible to obtain the missing data for birth year and gender so I decided to drop the null records.

In [10]:
bike.dropna(subset=['member_birth_year'], inplace=True)
bike.dropna(subset=['member_gender'], inplace=True)

Deal with incorrect data types¶

Convert data type of relevant features

In [11]:
bike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike['start_time'])
bike['member_birth_year'] = bike.member_birth_year.astype(int)
bike['user_type'] = bike.user_type.astype('category')
bike['member_gender'] = bike.member_gender.astype('category')
bike['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = bike.bike_share_for_all_trip.astype('category')

Extract the hour and day from trip's start time¶

The start_time column will be split into time of day and day of week values.

In [12]:
bike['start_hour'] = bike['start_time'].dt.hour
bike['start_day'] = bike['start_time'].dt.dayofweek

Convert birth year to age¶

It makes more sense to perform analysis on age rather than birth year. The values will be calculated based on the year 2019.

In [13]:
bike['member_age'] = 2019 - bike.member_birth_year

Drop columns that won't be used in the analysis¶

In [14]:
bike = bike[['duration_sec', 'user_type', 'member_gender', 'bike_share_for_all_trip', 'start_hour', 'start_day', 'member_age']]

User type¶

In [23]:
def plot_prop(col, col_name):
    # Count the frequency of unique values
    type_counts = col.value_counts()

    # Get the unique values in decreasing order of frequency
    type_order = type_counts.index

    # Returns the sum of all not-null values
    n_col = col.value_counts().sum()

    # Return the highest frequency 
    max_type_count = type_counts[0]

    # Return the maximum proportion
    max_prop = max_type_count / n_col

    # Produce a set of evenly spaced proportioned values
    tick_props = np.arange(0, max_prop, 0.1)

    # Use a list comprehension to create tick_names that we will apply to the tick labels
    tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]

    # Plot the data
    sb.countplot(data=bike, x=col_name, color=sb.color_palette()[0], order=type_order);
    
    # Change the tick locations and labels
    plt.yticks(tick_props * n_col, tick_names)
    plt.ylabel('proportion');
In [24]:
plot_prop(bike['user_type'], 'user_type')

Subscribers are entitled to unlimited rides so it isn't susprising for them to take more trips, which account for about 90% of the data.

Bike Share for All¶

Majority of the trips (about 90%) taken weren't eligible for the "Bike Share for All" program.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration variable's distribution is highly skewed and needed to be transformed to a log scale. Under a log scale, the data is unimodal with a peak at 796 seconds. The time of day variable has a bimodal distribution, with peaks at 8:00 and 17:00 and noticeably low counts during the early hours of the day. The day of week variable doesn't have a distinct trend, however it is evident that trips were more frequently taken during weekdays.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The age variable has unusual points above the 80 mark. These were difficult to clean, therefore they were ultimately dropped.

The distributions look very different. For non-discounted trips, there are two distinct peaks whereas for discounted trips, the frequency gradually increased from where the first peak should have been up to the second peak. This suggests that non-discounted trips are only taken mostly during peak hours while discounted trips are dispersed throughout the day.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The only feature that seemed to affect a trip's duration is the user type. Regular customers take less but slightly longer trips than subscribers do. Apart from that, the average duration didn't vary that much when compared with other features. The user type and Bike Share For All variables both affected the time of day and day of week. Subscribers have taken most of their trips during peak hours (8:00 and 17:00) and weekdays. Non-subscribers have taken trips a bit more spread out throughout the day and week. Discounted trips have the highest counts during peak hours and weekdays. Non-discounted trips were taken more consistently throughout the day and week.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The highest number of trips were taken by male subscribers. Gender doesn't seem to have a significant impact on the proportion between user types and on a user's eligibility for Bike Share for All program.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Customers consistently took longer trips regardless of the gender. This agrees the results from previous bivariate explorations and reinforces the relationship between user type and duration. Unspecified genders had a different effect on the relationship between the duration and Bike Share for All variable. However, this may be insignificant as other genders only account for 2% of the data.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It is interesting to see how the proportion of gender data affects the distribution of duration versus Bike Share for All.
